'''Donald Franciszek Tusk''' ({{IPAc-en|t|ʊ|s|k}} {{respell|TUUSK}}, {{IPA-pl|ˈdɔnalt fraɲˈt͡ɕiʂɛk ˈtusk|lang|Pl-Donald_Franciszek_Tusk.ogg}}; born 22 April 1957) is a Polish politician who was [[President of the European Council]] from 2014 to 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/european-council/president/biography/|title=Donald Tusk - Consilium|access-date=19 April 2017}}</ref> He served as the 14th prime minister of Poland from 2007 to 2014 and was a co-founder and chairman of the [[Civic Platform]] (''Platforma Obywatelska'') political party.<ref name=bbc>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28989875 |title=Italy's Mogherini and Poland's Tusk get top EU jobs |date=30 August 2014 |access-date=30 August 2014 |archive-date=31 August 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831010253/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28989875 |df=dmy}}</ref> On 20 November 2019, Tusk was elected as the president of the [[European People's Party]] (EPP), Europe's largest [[European political party|transnational political party]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/donald-tusk-elected-president-of-european-peoples-party/ |work=[[Politico]] |title=Donald Tusk elected President of European People's Party |date=20 November 2019 |access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref>

Tusk has been involved in Polish politics since the early 1990s, having founded several political parties and held elected office almost continuously since 1991. Tusk was one of the co-founders of the [[free market|free-market]]-orientated [[Liberal Democratic Congress]] party. He entered the [[Sejm]] (lower chamber of Poland's parliament) in 1991, but lost his seat in the 1993 election which went badly for the Congress.

In 1994, the Congress merged with the [[Democratic Union (Poland)|Democratic Union]] to form the [[Freedom Union (Poland)|Freedom Union]]. In 1997, Tusk was elected to the [[Senate of Poland|Senate]], and became its [[Marshal of the Senate|deputy speaker]]. In 2001, he co-founded another [[centre-right]] [[liberal conservative]] party, [[Civic Platform]] (PO), and he was again elected to the Sejm, and became its [[Marshal of the Sejm|deputy speaker]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Donald-Tusk |title=Donald Tusk |access-date=29 October 2017}}</ref>

He was elected prime minister in 2007 and with his party's victory in the [[2011 Polish parliamentary election]], he became the first Prime Minister to be re-elected since the [[History of Poland (1945–1989)#Politics of the last years of the People's Republic and the transition period|fall of communism in Poland]].<ref name="PSL want to continue coalition in next year's general election">{{cite news|title=PSL want to continue coalition in next year's general election|url=http://www.thenews.pl/national/?id=143700|publisher=[[Polskie Radio]]|date=18 November 2010|access-date=20 December 2010}}</ref> In 2014, he became [[president of the European Council]] and was re-elected to this position in 2017. He resigned as Polish prime minister to take the role, having been the longest-serving Prime Minister of the [[Third Polish Republic]] and the third longest-serving Prime Minister of Poland after [[Józef Cyrankiewicz]] and [[Piotr Jaroszewicz]].
